specifypositive: I don't have a daily commute so I have saved time and money and boredom not having to do that every day. My husband and I have spent very little over the last year and we have saved quite a lot more money that we had planned to, as we're saving up to buy our first home.
covidprecautionswhy: Because it's what is needed in order to minimise my chances of catching Covid and of avoiding me infecting other people, and because it will help to reduce infection rates in my country and mean we can get back to normal life sooner.
challenges: Yes. I find video calls draining and unsatisfying. They serve a purpose and mean that I can still communicate with and see family, friends and work colleagues. However, it's hard work doing so. I stress whether my internet connection is going to be strong enough for the call to go smoothly, whether I will look okay on camera and react and behave appropriately, whether there will be awkward pauses in conversation that seem more obvious than they are in real life. I also feel like I spend my whole life looking at a screen and my eyes are very tired all the time.
benefits: Not really although I do really appreciate the fact that doing a job that can be conducted entirely remotely has meant I've been able to work from home, stay safe, not catch Covid, and continue working so I haven't suffered financially.
anything_else: I feel like my life and the lives of people I care about are on hold and that this is causing suffering. For example, children who have lost out on so much school time and have suffered psychologically from being isolated from their friends for so long; people who have had to postpone weddings and graduations and really important life events; people who have not been able to visit loved ones before they died and/or not been able to attend the funerals of people they care about, which has made grieving difficult. My husband and I decided that we want to move away from the area we currently live in and purchase a house, but we can't do this until travel opens up again and we are sure the jobs market is going to remain stable. Covid has delayed this move by at least a year and we feel like we're in limbo in the meantime. My sister lives with her husband and children in New Zealand and I haven't seen them for 18 months and probably won't see them for at least another 6 months. I miss them so badly and my niece and nephew who are 2.5 and 4.5 are growing up so fast. I feel like I've missed such a huge part of their lives already and that breaks my heart.

vaccinelikelywhy: Vaccines are the best thing that happened to our society, they already saved millions of lives and will save more. Any potential risks are greatly outweighed by the benefits, and it's better to have a sore arm for 48h than to be ill in bed with Covid. I was diagnosed with covid in early March and although my symptoms were mild, I lost my sense of smell and it's still not back to normal. As I am an avid cook this really depressed me and I am still worried whether covid has caused permanent damage to my body. The vaccine will help to keep me safe, and hopefully avoid another infection. I have no reason to distrust a vaccine and that's why I am willing to take it. I'm thankful I even have a chance to be vaccinated as not everyone is so lucky.
specifypositive: I prefer to work remotely from home and my uni usually forces students to live on campus - I finally got to study from home. I am also less bored with my work because I conduct experiments for my PhD, and when they're lab based they can get very boring and repetitive. Now I test people online and it's a lot more exciting. I also got to spend so much quality time with my parents when they were furloughed from work and we were all together at home, watching movies, cooking etc.
covidprecautionswhy: My boyfriend doesn't live with me but I still want to see him, so we visit each other's houses, but we don't go into any other households and do not meet up with anyone else apart from our two households. I used to wear gloves to the store but I no longer do so because they are quite uncomfortable, my hands get sweaty and they're expensive to buy. I use hand sanitizer when I can, and try to keep my distance from people, but sometimes it's just not possible (e.g. in supermarket etc.). I sometimes go to the store just to buy 1-2 non-essential things.
benefits: Yes, I like working from home, I'm less bored, more focussed, I'm more comfortable during meetings, no commute etc.
anything_else: I don't think people talk enough about how loss of smell after covid can affect people mentally - I took it really hard when everything tasted like cardboard and when I was unable to cook properly. I'm still not fully recovered and worry about my sense of smell not returning to normal daily.

I am aware that long covid can result in strokes and alzeimers in the long run. She has had to return to work now because she could not survive on sick pay. However as a result of me pushing for her to get a covid jab before returning to work, this seems to have kick started her immune system again and although still breathless, it has stopped the swelling in her hands every time she tries to exercise and also the redness on her face and peeling feet. There needs to be lot more research and help for those who are now suffering with long covid because this dreadful government put profit before people.

vaccinelikelywhy: For me personally, I do not feel comfortable taking the vaccine. No matter how many people say it is safe, in reality, they have no idea the long term affects of the vaccine since no one has had it long enough to see the outcome. It is an experimental vaccine and skipped many of the stages that vaccines go through in order to be quickly distributed to slow the spread of COVID. Additionally, I am extremely allergic to soy, which seems to be in at least two, if not all of the vaccines. Since I am so allergic, the vaccine would be a big risk for me.
